Dont be scared, she cant hurt you! 
Just a story... 
There's something in the field!
Who's out there? Show yourself! 
See, its just a fla- #$&%. 
Nothing to be afraid of. 
I feel glares. 
Brother, what is that? What is that? 
ITS ALIVE!
NO! Don't leave me! 
Brother! Open the door! 
LET ME IN! 
She's still out there... 
She moves around at night. 
Cut! Reap! Shear! Sow! 
She's hunting us. She knows what we're afraid of! 
Come closer. Closer... 
HELP ME! 
We can't get out! 
She wont leave! 
No, no! Please, no! 
IT'S IN THE HOUSE! 
Hide, fandeads... Hide! 
Don't open your eyes! Keep running! 
Fandeads! Fandeads! 
Don't let go! 
I'll save you, little light!
I'm always here, my little hero! 
They haven't come back from the fields, it's been three days. 
All alone, lost in the dark. 
Fear. Agony. Nightmares. 
Addiction. Secrets. Horror.
Guilty. Guilty. Guilty! 
All your fault! All your fault! 
Help me... 
Someone, hear me... 
I'm lost. Afraid... 
The Necromancer? 
You're not... real...

author: HelloImNothing
text:
Is there anyone who learned Japanese?

Like the Alphabets alone?

Was it hard?

author: Hudaef Cares?
text: @HelloImNothing  Oh yeah. The Japanese use 3 writing systems: Hiragana, Katakana and Kanji. Luckily if you memorize Hiragana and Katakana you can understand Japanese so much more. Kanji is pain shuba even with native Japanese so don't get too intimidated with it.

author: HelloImNothing
text:
@Hudaef Cares? 

Easiest to Hardest
1. Hiragana
2. Katakana
3. Kanji

Just by looking at Kanji and comparing it with other forms of writing in Japanese (Hiragana and Katakana)

I already know it's hard, lmao.

author: Hudaef Cares?
text: @HelloImNothing  Personally I already know Hiragana and Katakana, so now I'm leaving Kanji for later as I'm focusing more on vocabulary and grammar coz I'm learning Japanese to understand, not to read. Still can't quite wrap my head around sentence structure and particles lol

author: Lelouch Vi Britania
text: same

author: Ian Anderson
text: @HelloImNothing  the japanese written language is more like two alphabets and a word bank. i'm learning hiragana now and it is pretty easy and i doubt that katakana is too difficult; however, kanji, the word bank, is significantly more difficult. i learned chinese for a bit before now and it was a royal pain in the ass, however i do have an advantage when learning japanese now just because kanji is rly just chinese characters. it's definitely not an easy task but the two 46 character alphabets should be easy if you stick to it. good luck if you ever try kanji tho

author: HelloImNothing
text:
@Ian Anderson 

Haha, I only memorize three kanjis which are one, two and three.

一、二、三。

I did learn numeral kanjis for up to ten but I keep forgetting about how I write it.

I will never progress, haha!
